title: For Sale/Trade:  Star Model B 9mm Semi-Automatic Pistol
postcontent:
This Star Model B was manufactured in 1943, arsenal refinished at the end of WWII, and was still in cosmolene when I purchased it.  I cleaned it thoroughly, lubricated it, put ~35 rounds through it, and cleaned and lubricated it afterwards.  The pictures tell the story of the condition.  The grips are wooden and the 8 round magazine is original and unmodified.

In case you're unfamiliar with the Star B, it was manufactured by Star Bonifacio Echeverria in Spain.  It looks and feels similar to the Browning Model 1911, but is chambered in 9 mm.  It has other differences from the 1911, and parts are not interchangeable.  The parent design for this gun is the Star Model A, which is chambered for 9X23 mm Largo.  When Star modified the Model A to fire the 9 mm Luger cartridge, they initially installed internal spacer blocks in the rear portion of the magazines to prevent a sloppy fit of the shorter 9x19 catridges.  They made changes to the Model B during WWII, and one of them was to abandon production of these costlier magazines.  The magazine with this pistol is this unmodified type.  Some Star B owners install an internal spacer in the magazine to eliminate the sloppy fit of the cartridges and improve reliability.  I have not shot it enough to warrant the time and effort to do this.

To see an electronic copy of the owners manual, go here:  www.stevespages.com/pdf/star.pdf

Must present government ID showing you are a resident of Ohio of legal age to purchase a handgun.

Serious buyers may request high resolution photographs.

title: For Sale:  AK-47 (not a wasr)
postcontent:
(NOTE: Sorry folks, this rifle is SOLD. Please hold any further inquiries.) 
I hate to let this go, because at the very least, the further importation of these is extremely likely to be halted soon, causing values to skyrocket and availability to plummet.
That being said, I'm selling one of my very favorite toys, my Lancaster-built AK-47. This is a Romanian AK, but it's not a cheap,lowly WASR, these are built on American receivers w/ G2 trigger group, from the Romanian "G Models" ( G stands for 'Guardia' and were their genuine military issue rifles.) I am the original owner of this rifle, purchasing it new about 8 years ago, directly from Lancaster Arms in Arizona ( and shipped here to Columbus.)
At the time, Lancaster was very highly regarded by AK afficianados, but as order volume increased, their ability to maintain the same quality began to suffer after a few years, as did their reputation.
But the older Lancasters are still widely considered excellent rifles, as this one definitely is.
One of their cool production trademarks was that they Parkerized the bare metal, and then used that as a base for the Gun-Kote baked-on epoxy finish, that looks great and is completely corrosion resistant.
The rifle has only been fired a few times, and is in pristine condition. The chrome bore is clean and crisp. The front sights and gas tube are perfectly straight, and the rivet heads are perfectly formed, and magazines fit firmly ( like I said, it ain't a WASR).
I installed an ERGO-Grip myself, as they are much more comfortable and ergonomic that those cheesy,stock AK grips.  I also installed the larger, Bulgarian flash-hider seen in the pics. The rifle has both the cleaning rod and cleaning kit concealed in the butt-stock.
Included is the green-web AK sling,and three,30-round magazines, including the vintage Russian (Tula) Bake-Lite magazine seen in the photos ( these are expensive, difficult to find collector items on their own). The other mags are a standard east-block steel mag, and a polymer Tapco.
Also inlcuded are 5 boxes of Wolf ammo.
I haven't decided if I'm taking this to the Eastmann gunshow this weekend,I may be there.
This is for sale to Georgia Residents with valid drivers license (I'll sell to Ala. residents, but that will require an FFL transfer in Phenix City.)
Asking $1200,firm, and from what I'm currently seeing of the AK market, this quite reasonable for a rifle of this quality ( the big local gunstore  {you know who I mean} has only 2 AK's in stock, both used Romanians, and asking $1100 plus tax, and NO cool upgrades,ammo or accessories.)

title: For Sale:  Lake City 5.56 Green Tip Ammo
postcontent:
Sale Pending.  I will update by mid-afternoon Saturday.

I have 2000 rounds of Lake City Ammunition for sale and will ship at the buyer's expense.

$650/1000 or will split for $.75/round

This hard to find 5.56x45mm XM855 ammunition is perfect for your 5.56 chambered AR-15 and it is manufactured at the famed Lake City Army Ammunition Plant (LCAAP). This ammo is rugged and reliable having been produced on the same production line that produces ammunition for our U.S. military!

This XM855 ammunition is also commonly known as "green tip" or "penetrator" ammo for the steel tip located at the front of the bullet. These "green tip" bullets are copper jacketed, lead core, with a steel tip at the front of the bullet.

Lake City is currently operated under contract by ATK (parent company of Federal, CCI, and Speer) who is allowed to sell excess production to the civilian market. 

This ammunition which is manufactured on the same production line that as the U.S. military's has a few differences than commercially manufactured 223 ammo. First, this ammo has both a primer sealant and a case/mouth sealant designed to help prevent moisture intrusion helping your ammo to last longer. Second, this ammunition must have the annealing marks left around the neck of the cartridge case. Brass cases are formed from a flat sheet of metal and are made through the cup and draw process. With each drawing step that the brass undergoes it becomes brittle and must be heat treated for it to become workable again for the next draw. After the last draw the brass runs across a series of flames aimed at the neck of the case to make the metal malleable. Evidence of this final annealing step at Lake City must be left on the cases so that military inspectors can verify that the cases have been properly annealed. So, the discoloration on the cases is simply a cosmetic appearance and is actually a sign that this final quality step was performed. In fact, Lake City brass is considered by many reloading experts to be the best brass in the world for reloading 5.56 ammo.

This ammo is brass-cased, boxer-primed, non-corrosive, and reloadable. For quality 5.56 ammo, it doesn't get any better than Lake City production!

title: For Sale:  LWRC AR-15 AR chambered 6.8 SPC Gas Piston better than COLT 5.56 +4 mags
postcontent:
New Years Price drop 12/31/12:  $2,500 to $2,400. Large drop first "payment sent" takes it.

I am selling LWRC AR chambered in 6.8 spc.  

If you are not familiar with the ammunition do a simple Google search. The ammunition was developed by Remmington and USSOCOM to address 5.56mm deficiencies and potentially replace it. It is midway between the 5.5645mm NATO and 7.6251mm NATO in bore diameter and velocity (Wikipedia) 6.8 special boasts up to 40-50% more kinetic energy than the 5.56 and in terms of weight only about 30% heavier so you can carry more bang for your buck.

The lower has not been fired.  It is a LWRC stripped lower marked 6.8 spc with a Stags Lower Parts Kit (LPK) installed.  The complete lower also includes a Colt Safety, Magpul MOE grip,  Commercial size receiver extension, Heavy Buffer, LWRCs new trigger guard, Snake Skin Panels, and Magpul MOE stock.

The upper only has 600 rounds through it.  The barrel is 14.5 stainless Lother Walther barrel thats ceracoated black.   It has a 1:10 twist rate, with a pinned and welded Phantom flash suppressor (this was all factory work at LWRC, when they offered this model).  Also included is a LWRC Nickle-Teflon bolt carrier and 6.8 CMT bolt and Standard Charging handle.  There is no rear sight, but there is a GG&G triple clamped flip up front sight gas block (used only as a front sight, not a gas block).

Your FFL must be able to accept from an individual. Money Order is preferred form of payment.  If you need to do Paypal please add +4% and be discreet.  Please note that firearm is not in my possession. I have paid for this weapon and decided to resell. The shipper is an employee of an LWRC distributor. This weapon was part of his personal collection.

While the upper has a relatively low round count considering its age, it has been used as a display upper since '07. So there are visible handling marks, most notable around to forward section of the rail (these should be visible in the photos). The lower looks quite new. 

The gun will come with one used PRI mag (pictured), one new in bag PRI 25rd mag and two new C Product mags. The used steel PRI mags have had surface rust, which have been cleaned off. There gun is completely functional and in good shape.

This weapon new would be $2000-$2200NIB before the gun scare AR-15 craze. This firearm is selling at better value than other low end to entry level ARs that are selling for TWICE as much as they were before. The mark up is minimal or virtually nonexistent as LWRCs are the best gas-piston ARs on the market.
6.8SPC is easier to find than MARKED UP 5.56/.223.  5.56 is selling for about (70cents/round) 6.8 (.80cents/round)

Also listed here:
http://www.gunbroker.com/Auction/ViewItem.aspx?Item=324236350

WILL SHIP TO AN FFL ONLY.
